# Edge \- From Error Messages to Problem Details

# Background

- The work around this issue has already been done in the Data Hub, for the backend, see https://github.com/hivemq/hivemq-edge/pull/993

## The Problem Details standard

The current format used in Edge (see [API Design on HiveMQ Atlassian](https://hivemq.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/HMQ/pages/580518015/API+Design#Must:-Use-JSON-Error-Messages)) is loosely based on the Problem Details standard, but doesn’t meet its requirements

- The response MUST use the `application/problem+json` media type
- The payload MUST have a `type`
- The payload can support multiple errors, but they MUST be instances of the same type

_When designed to accommodate it, problem-specific extensions can convey more than one instance of the same problem type_

[_https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9457.html\#name-the-problem-details-json-ob_](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9457.html#name-the-problem-details-json-ob)

- The `detail` property of the payload is user-facing, it MUST contain as much context as possible, but MUST NOT have to be parsed by the client to extract actionable information

_Consumers SHOULD NOT parse the "detail" member for information; extensions are more suitable and less error-prone ways to obtain such information._

[_https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9457.html\#name-detail_](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9457.html#name-detail)

## Specifying the Problem Details with OpenAPi specs

To do

- Create a registry of problem details for HiveMQ
- Use OpenAPI to formally describe the schema of the different types of errors supported
- Use `type` in a Problem Detail, as a URI referencing the relevant schema

With code generation from the OpenAPI specification, both backend and frontend will now have a fully specified list of errors, expressed as an unambiguous **Problem Details** payload.

# Examples

## Datahub \- DataPolicy is invalid

### The current payload

Publishing a new data policy fails with 400

```
curl 'http://localhost:8080/api/v1/data-hub/data-validation/policies' \
  -H 'Accept: application/json' \
  --data-raw '{"id":"vcfvbvb","matching":{"topicFilter":"topic/example/1"},"onSuccess":{"pipeline":[{"functionId":"Delivery.redirectTo","arguments":{"topic":"test"},"id":"fdgdfg"}]}}'

```

```javascript
{
  "type": "DataPolicyInvalid",
  "title": "DataPolicy is invalid",
  "detail": "DataPolicy failed validation",
  "status": 400,
  "errors": [
    {
      "detail": "Required field missing",
      "parameter": "produced by policy validation: Required field 'onSuccess.pipeline[0].arguments.applyPolicies' is missing."
    }
  ]
}
```

There are three issues with the response

- `Type` is a URI as expected, but it is encouraged to be a resolvable URI, for future-proofing
- `Detail` is a user-facing string explanation specific to this occurrence of the type of error. The current text repeats the `type` rather than explaining the occurrence (see errors)
- `Errors` contain a list of problems (one in the example) explaining the error. They MUST be problem details, and of the same type as the main, which is not the case
  - No `type` or `title` given, as assumed to be of the container \[?\]
  - `Detail` is used, whereas it should be `title` (user-facing text associated with a new type of error)
  - `Parameter` should have been `detail` (describes the occurrence of the error) and violates the “no parsing” requirement.  
    It contains a mix of user-facing string explaining the occurrence of the error (`Required field is missing`), a machine-readable parameter (`'onSuccess.pipeline[0].arguments.applyPolicies'`) and (maybe) a context (`produced by policy validation`)

A fourth issue might not necessarily be one

- `Title` SHOULD NOT change from occurrence to occurrence of the problem; `”DataPolicy is invalid”` is therefore expected to be the user-facing string always associated with the `DataPolicyInvalid` type

### The Problem Detail payload

These are the design decisions for refactoring this particular type of error

- Every error response from the `api/v1/data-hub/data-validation/policies` API will have `DataPolicyInvalid` as `type`
- It is a generic container that MUST have AT LEAST ONE problem detail in the `errors` extension
- The `detail` provides a summary of the returned errors
- The `errors` extension is a MUST property of this type of error
- The `errors` MUST be valid problem details and can be of different `types`
- The `code` contains the correlation ID of the occurrence, to use for tracing back to the app’s error log

A refactoring of the error could then be as follows:

```
{
  "type": "DataPolicyInvalid",
  "title": "DataPolicy is invalid",
  "detail": "The data policy cannot be validated because one requirement is not met",
  "status": 400,
  "code": "b83772eb-8bc1-4d63-8e57-cafefe117087",
  "errors": [
    {
      "type": "RequiredFieldMissing",
      "title": "Required field missing",
      "detail": "The field applyPolicies is missing from the policy",
      "path": "$.onSuccess.pipeline[0].arguments.applyPolicies"
      "rule": "policy-validation-required-field"
    }
  ]
}
```

### The openAPI specification

Our error repository now contains two types of errors

- `DataPolicyInvalid` is a container for all errors associated with Data Policy validation. It fully implements the definition of `ProblemDetails`
- `RequiredFieldMissing` is an error describing a missing field within a request payload. It has the following properties
  - `path` \[REQUIRED\]: a JSON-PATH string referencing the property of the payload that triggered the error
  - `rule`: a reference to the rule of the internal validation engine that triggered the error
- The list of `errors` cannot be `Problem Details`
  - They are of different types, depending on the different causes of the error in the first place
  - The `status` might be different if used as a Problem Details
- Two solutions
  - Remove the top container, which in effect doesn’t add any value to the nature of the error (the policy is invalid by the nature of a 400 returned to the API endpoint). Use the `RequiredFieldMissing` directly as a Problem Detail, without the `errors` property. It means error messages MUST have a single error type
  - Maintain the `errors` property, but its content is NOT `ProblemDetails`. They are `ProblemDetailCause`, with a simplified payload

### The client side

![][image1]

- **Title** and **detail** are now guaranteed to be proper user-facing strings and can be used in the toast.
- A “more details” link could expand the toast by adding the list of **details** from all included **errors**
- The type of the extension error (`RequiredFieldMissing`) clearly indicates a missing configuration element, with `path` containing the reference to the missing element. The client's internal logic unambiguously identifies the “Operation” element as the source of the error, allowing the UI to highlight the node (“alert”) and display the error message associated with that particular error (title and detail again).

## Datahub \- DataPolicy is invalid

Modifying the policy above and publishing it

```
curl 'http://localhost:8080/api/v1/data-hub/data-validation/policies/vcfvbvbff' \
  -X 'PUT' \
  -H 'Accept: application/json' \
  --data-raw '{"id":"vcfvbvbff","matching":{"topicFilter":"topic/example/12"},"onSuccess":{"pipeline":[{"functionId":"Serdes.deserialize","arguments":{"schemaId":"rfrtfr","schemaVersion":"fddf"},"id":"fdgdfg"}]}}'

```

### The current payload

```
{
  "type": "DataPolicyInvalid",
  "title": "DataPolicy is invalid",
  "detail": "DataPolicy failed validation",
  "status": 400,
  "errors": [
    {
      "detail": "If 'Serdes.deserialize' function is present in the pipeline, 'Serdes.serialize' function must be present as well.",
      "parameter": "function"
    },
    {
      "detail": "Illegal value",
      "parameter": "produced by policy validation: Field 'onSuccess.pipeline[0].arguments.schemaVersion' has illegal value 'fddf'. Value cannot be parsed to a valid schema version."
    }
  ]
}

```

### The Problem Detail payload

```
{
  "type": "DataPolicyInvalid",
  "title": "DataPolicy is invalid",
  "detail": "The data policy cannot be validated because two requirements are not met",
  "status": 400,
  "code": "573ac428-ec14-4fd5-8135-806cedb81041",
  "errors": [
    {
      "type": "FunctionDependency",
      "title": "A function is missing in the pipeline",
      "detail": "If 'Serdes.deserialize' function is present in a pipeline, 'Serdes.serialize' function must be present as well.",
      "path": "$.onSuccess.pipeline[0].functionId"
	"condition": "Serdes.deserialize",
	"dependencies": ["Serdes.serialize"],
      "rule": "policy-validation-function-dependency"
    },
    {
      "type": "IllegalValue",
      "title": "Illegal value",
      "detail": "Schema version 'fddf' cannot be parsed to a valid schema version",
      "path": "$.onSuccess.pipeline[0].arguments.schemaVersion"
	"value": "fddf",
	"remedial": "Did you mean 'food'? "
      "rule": "policy-validation-schema-unknown"
    }

  ]
}
```

### The openAPI specification

- Reusing `DataPolicyInvalid`
- Two new error types created:
  - `FunctionDependency` \=\> `path`, `condition`, `dependencies`
  - `IllegalValue` \=\> `path`, `value`
- To consider:
  - Could `IllegalValue` offer a `remedial` property if the backend knows a “related” value that might work?

# OpenAPI Specification

```yaml
openapi: 3.1.0
info:
 contact:
   url: https://www.hivemq.com
 description: List of errors
 title: HiveMQ Edge REST API - Problem Details Registry
 version: 2025.6-SNAPSHOT
paths:
 /api/v1/data-hub/data-validation/policies:
   post:
     description: A mockup of the Data Policy Validation endpoint
     responses:
       '400':
         content:
           application/problem+json:
             schema:
               $ref: '#/components/schemas/DataPolicyInvalid'
         description: Error in validation request.
components:
 schemas:
   ProblemDetails:
     type: object
     properties:
       type:
         type: string
         format: uri
         description: A URI reference that identifies the problem type.
         maxLength: 1024
       status:
         type: integer
         description: The HTTP status code generated by the origin server for this occurrence of the problem.
         format: int32
         minimum: 100,
         maximum: 599
       title:
         type: string
         description: A short, human-readable summary of the problem type. It should not change from occurrence to occurrence of the problem, except for purposes of localization.
         maxLength": 1024
       detail:
         type: string
         description: A human-readable explanation specific to this occurrence of the problem.
         maxLength: 4096
       instance:
         type: string,
         description: A URI reference that identifies the specific occurrence of the problem. It may or may not yield further information if dereferenced.
         maxLength: 1024
       code:
         type: string
         description: An API specific error code (correlation ID) aiding the provider team understand the error based on their own potential taxonomy or registry.
     required:
       - detail
   ProblemDetailCause:
     type: object
     required:
       - detail
       - path
     properties:
       type:
         type: string
         format: uri
         description: A URI reference that identifies the cause of the problem.
         maxLength: 1024
       title:
         type: string
         description: A short, human-readable summary of the problem type. It should not change from occurrence to occurrence of the problem, except for purposes of localization.
         maxLength": 1024
       detail:
         type: string
         description: A human-readable explanation specific to this occurrence of the problem.
         maxLength: 4096
       rule:
         type: string
         format: json-path
   DataPolicyInvalid:
     allOf: # Combines the main `ProblemDetails` schema with `errors`-specific properties
       - $ref: "#/components/schemas/ProblemDetails"
       - type: object
         properties:
           errors:
             description: A list of causes of the specific occurrence of the problem
             type: array
             items:
               anyOf:
                 - $ref: '#/components/schemas/RequiredFieldMissing'
                 - $ref: '#/components/schemas/FunctionDependency'
   RequiredFieldMissing:
     allOf:
       - $ref: "#/components/schemas/ProblemDetailCause"
       - type: object
         properties:
           path:
             type: string
             format: json-path
     required:
       - detail
       - path
   ErrorX:
     allOf:
       - $ref: "#/components/schemas/ProblemDetail"
       - type: object
         properties:
           condition:
             type: string
           dependencies:
             type: array
             items:
               type: string
         required:
           - detail
           - condition
           - dependencies
   IllegalValue:
     allOf:
       - $ref: "#/components/schemas/ProblemDetailCause"
       - type: object
         properties:
           value:
             type: string
         required:
           - detail
           - value
\
```
